@hyanrarvey what you’re saying makes tons of sense. I guess I just don’t feel like my currently released credits show what I truly feel I’m capable of, hard to confidently ask for a higher rate when people around me are good too and charging similarly. 

Sort of that “be undeniable” thing; i feel like some of the newer stuff I’ve done falls into that, where the mixes are *genuinely* fucking good, not just better than hobbyist but not competitive. 

Anyway, I may experiment this year with a dramatic mix rate increase. You’ve all inspired me.

@river 

I understood them to do opposite jobs, right? RBass does some kind of trickery to generate the impression of low end in small speakers, but doesn’t actually add a low octave - just upper harmonics that suggest it (afaik). 

Lo-Air synthesises a real tone an octave below the source, or at least I thought it did? Like Avid Pro Subharmonic.

@BoozleBAM I know this could and most times goes without saying but make sure you do a “save as” for a separate session before you start flexing and editing your drums. Like @Slow Hand said, you can easily edit the life out of a performance and it’s good to 
1) be able to go back to how you recorded it exactly if you mess up and start chasing your tail (I’ve been there) 
2) it’s good to just be able to a/b as a gut check

@cian riordan I will say, when I do LCR micing like you’ve mentioned and seem to do often, a hihat mic can really help push it forward to balance with the other cymbals. 

I just think so often hihats are too loud, played too loud, etc. but the better the drummer is the more useful a hihat mic is. 

I also just like talking shit on HH mics for fun.

I can already feel my temptation to alley-oop one in, only to find myself blocked cus I’m not with it like that.

Okay so newby question, who here will is willing to be my ‘STD Momma’ bro?

@Josh looks promising.
